
## Option 1: Pyber Analysis

•	Rural has the lowest number of rides of the city types. This would be due to a lower population and more cars since fewer means of transportation are available. 

•	Rural also has the highest fare average of the three city types as well. This would be due to the need to travel further since rural areas have a more sparling landscape with places spread further out than in an Urban setting.

•	There is a correlation between number of rides and the average fare per city. Urban cities the highest number of rides, thehighest number of drivers and had the lowest average fare of the three types of cities.

•	Urban cities had both the largest percentage of total rides and percentage of drivers.

```python
#Color Dictionary 
color_scheme = {'Gold':'#FFD700', 'Light Sky Blue':'#87CEFA', 'Light Coral':'#F08080'}
city_color = {'Urban': color_scheme['Light Coral'], 'Suburban': color_scheme['Gold'], 'Rural': color_scheme['Light Sky Blue']}
```


```python
# Tell matplotlib to create a scatter plot based upon the above data        

#plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
#plt.figtext(.95, .75, "Note: \nCircle size corelates with driver count per city")
plt.scatter(urban_df["Total Rides Per City"], 
            urban_df["Ave City Fare"], marker="o", 
            color = city_color['Urban'], edgecolors="black", label="Urban", 
            s=urban_df["Total Drivers Per City"]*10, alpha=0.75, linewidth=1)
plt.scatter(suburban_df["Total Rides Per City"], 
            suburban_df["Ave City Fare"], marker="o", 
            color = city_color['Suburban'], edgecolors="black", label="Suburban", 
            s=suburban_df["Total Drivers Per City"]*10, alpha=0.75, linewidth=1)
plt.scatter(rural_df["Total Rides Per City"], 
            rural_df["Ave City Fare"], marker="o", 
            color = city_color['Rural'], edgecolors="black", label="Rural", 
            s=rural_df["Total Drivers Per City"]*10, alpha=0.75, linewidth=1)

#Plot lables
plt.suptitle('Pyber Ride Sharing Data (2016)')
plt.title('Note : Size of Bubble Corresponds to Number of Drivers per City')
plt.xlabel('Number of Rides per City')
plt.ylabel('Average Fare per City')

#Set the upper and lower limits of our y axis
plt.ylim(15,45)

# Set the upper and lower limits of our x axis
plt.xlim(0,40)

#create legend

lgnd = plt.legend(frameon = True, edgecolor = 'black', scatterpoints=1, fontsize=10, title="City Types")
lgnd.legendHandles[0]._sizes = [30]
lgnd.legendHandles[1]._sizes = [30]
lgnd.legendHandles[2]._sizes = [30]

plt.savefig("RideShareByCity.png")
plt.show()
```
